Text.Value: I'm cautiously optimistic. Though with the time left to us, and the amount still to be done, it's best we don't take anything for granted.
You won't get the Crown from the Netherbrain without my help. I won't let you.
I still prefer my odds if I don't turn myself into a crater the size of the Lower City.

EditorData.NodeContext: bit of an edge to it - pissed off that you suggested it

Text.Value: I made a promise to my goddess. One I will do my best to keep. For the sake of this city, I can only hope that my best will be enough.
What do you think I should do?
I hope that wasn't our last kiss. I'd take a thousand more if I could.
'When?' I'm glad you have such confidence in our endeavour. I confess, my own's not constructed from such immutable materials.
Glad to hear it.
Relinquish the stones, and you place your fate in the hands of a creature whose trustworthiness is hardly guaranteed.
It seems the brain's more reluctant to let go of the crown than we anticipated.
Do you think we stand a chance against the Netherbrain?
Do you think we stand a chance against the Netherbrain?
Leave.
I hope that wasn't our only chance. We must get hold of that crown.
So be it - I will be ready, whatever you decide.
We've a city to save. I think it's about time we got started.

EditorData.NodeContext: Determined

Text.Value: Quite the choice you're faced with: surrender the Netherstones to a mind flayer, or surrender your soul and become one.

EditorData.NodeContext: Serious, this is a big decision

Text.Value: Whatever you decide, do not delay for too long. Every moment we hesitate, the Crown may slip further out of reach.

EditorData.NodeContext: Reining in his impatience

Text.Value: As it stands, I see no option free of sacrifice in one form or another. So the question becomes - what are you willing to give up?
I'd be lying if I said it wouldn't take some getting used to, but what can a few extra tentacles do to a bond as strong as ours?

EditorData.NodeContext: not overly bothered, takes it in his stride

Text.Value: Keep the stones, and you relinquish the very essence of your being. Your soul, your emotions, your purpose. You would lose everything, and might live with such a loss for eternity.
Ask me again when the illithid scourge has been wiped from this city, and I'll have an answer for you. Until then - it's best not to count on anything.
Good. We'll put that little outburst down to the shock of the circumstances, and move swiftly on.
Leave.
Now, let's drop the matter, before I feel obliged to detonate the orb just to put an end to the bloody business altogether.

EditorData.NodeContext: bit of an edge to it - pissed off that you suggested it

Text.Value: We're facing a Netherbrain. Lose, and you'll never become a god anyway.
Separating the crown from that monstrosity will be harder than we imagined. It might be time to reconsider our strategy.

EditorData.NodeContext: Cogs beginnign to whir. He might end up offering to blow himself up after this

Text.Value: If you seek my input, you've only to ask.

EditorData.NodeContext: Serious, this is a big decision

Text.Value: I don't dare to imagine making such a decision when there's the small matter of the enormous brain beneath the crown still to overcome.
Fate seems determined to make a mindflayer of you, as it would make a cataclysm of me. Make your choice - the orb will be there regardless.

EditorData.NodeContext: Gallows humour/grim
EditorData.logicalname: ORPHEUS ULTIMATUM, WILLING TO DIE IN EMPEROR ULTIMATUM

Text.Value: Who knows what shape these final moments of ours might assume? Not I. Not Mystra. Not even you. But whatever my fate might be, I'll be glad to greet it in such fine company.
The Karsite Weave is primed for godhood, as soon as we have the Crown within our grasp.
I trust you to know the course we must take. But my offer stands - if none wish to shoulder the illithid's burden, the orb would achieve the same ends.
I'd need a ream of parchment longer than an elder brain's stem to capture the tumult I feel at that particular prospect.
If the path we tread were easy, there'd be a queue of fools willing to walk it. Alas, it isn't. And such grim choices must fall to us.
Beyond that, the choice is yours to make, and I wouldn't dare to impose myself on one faced with making such a sacrifice.

EditorData.NodeContext: A bit snippy - making a point of not trying to convince the player as they just did with him

Text.Value: I sense your resolve falters, so allow me to provide some encouragement: we are not going to lose, and I am going to get that crown.

EditorData.NodeContext: bit of an edge to it - pissed off that you suggested it

Text.Value: I don't think it was.
Why exactly would I choose that course now, when I have so much to live for?
Barely awake a moment, and the prince of the githyanki demands you surrender your soul?

EditorData.NodeContext: Serious, this is a big decision

Text.Value: I confess, in my head I saw that going a lot less amicably. I hope our newly-freed ally proves more reliable than the last.
The risk will be well worth the gain - we need only to hold our nerve through these final tribulations, and the crown will be ours. Everything will be ours.
Actually, that's not why I wanted to talk to you. It's about the orb...
Come now - turning on each other will hardly improve our chances of survival.

EditorData.NodeContext: hint of an eye roll - you're really trying that shit on me? a bit annoyed you tried

Text.Value: I don't dare to picture the crown in my hands - not when there's the small matter of an enormous, city-conquering brain beneath it.
The elder brain was already a formidable foe, but the Netherbrain is on the cusp of achieving a godhood of its own.

EditorData.NodeContext: The stakes of the matter - the netherbrain is nigh on unstoppable

Text.Value: Fate seems determined to make a mindflayer of you. It remains your choice, as the crown remains mine.

EditorData.NodeContext: Reining in his impatience

Text.Value: The scent of Netheril hangs heavy in this place. The brain is close, as is the crown. I'm glad we face such a monster together.
However, the sharpest tongues sometimes make the finest points. And your urgency is not unwarranted -  our circumstances have changed.

EditorData.NodeContext: With a sigh - reluctantly accepting he needs to think more carefully on this

Text.Value: Even you - after the dreams we've shared.
There is, of course one more course to consider. The orb. None need shoulder the illithid's burden, if that is what you decide.
If you need advice, I'll do my best - though I have to say I've not much to draw on in this case. It's rather a unique predicament to have landed yourself with.

EditorData.NodeContext: Serious, this is a big decision

Text.Value: These could be our final moments. Time enough for a kiss.
You're right. It's too late to change course now. We need to claim the crown.
I assure you it remains stable as ever, in spite of our encounter with the Netherbrain.
The aura of Netheril hangs heavy in this place. The brain is close, as is the crown. As is victory, dare we begin to hope...
Is that not the very nature of chasing divinity?
Strolling these streets together would have been quite magical, in other circumstances. This is all a tad apocalyptic for my liking.
We'll soon be close enough for you to use the orb. How are you feeling?
We'll soon be close enough for you to use the orb. How are you feeling?
I'm getting rather tired of how often those I care about seem to reach the same conclusion.
I challenged my goddess, defied her will, and promised her destruction.
Fail to get the crown after all that, and if the embarrassment doesn't finish me off, Mystra might.
Pessimism like that is hardly going to improve our chances. But - I will begrudgingly admit that circumstances have somewhat changed.

EditorData.NodeContext: Scoffing a bit, but reluctantly acknowledging you're not wrong

Text.Value: Sacrificing myself to destroy it wasn't exactly the form of immortality I hoped for, but perhaps the time for hope has passed altogether. Now we need certainty.

EditorData.NodeContext: trying to convince himself of this path, grim/gloomy as he comes to terms with it

Text.Value: You're okay - thank the heavens and hells and everything in between. I thought the brain would take you from me.

EditorData.NodeContext: Utter relief

Text.Value: But if, if, we overcome that obstacle, I will do everything.
Though I confess, the prospect of trying to outwit a brain the size of Mount Waterdeep is a challenge even for me.
How do you feel about using the orb, if all else fails?
How do you feel about using the orb, if all else fails?
I stand here on the precipice of divinity - a course you encouraged me to pursue, I might add - and now you come to tell me to blow myself up?
The orb? Why ever would we need to talk about that?
Gale... I think we should consider using the orb as Mystra intended. To blow up the Netherbrain.
As for your current predicament - it doesn't matter to me who holds the Netherstones, so long as they they are mine to claim once the brain is dispatched.

EditorData.NodeContext: Stern

Text.Value: I'm not sure I ever considered the Emperor an ally, exactly, but even so, it's strange to know we're on our own at last.
You're being selfish. You're risking all of our lives, our souls even - for the chance to make yourself immortal.
You'll soon have far greater things to be glad of - I promise you that.
What will you do when we get hold of the crown?
What will you do when we get hold of the crown?
When this is all over, we'll have time enough to unpick the specifics of your new condition. Psionics alone could take months to thoroughly evaluate, not to mention the matter of your diet -

EditorData.NodeContext: Getting excited at the prospect of learning about your new form

Text.Value: But I'm getting ahead of myself. We've a Netherbrain to defeat. Then we get to the fun stuff.

EditorData.NodeContext: Catching himself, delaying gratification

Text.Value: The High Hall was once a beacon of promise, of wisdom, of celebration. Now... well , it's just a beacon, and for all manner of horrors. A pity.

EditorData.NodeContext: Referring to the fact the high hall is on fire/wrecked

Text.Value: Please - I need a moment.

EditorData.NodeContext: Mentally preparing himself for the prospect he might die when you face the brain

Text.Value: How do you like my new look?
But I'm ready, if that's the word you need to hear. If you call on me, I will not let you down.
All I can say is - whatever choice you make, if it leads us to taking the Crown it will be worth it. And I will ensure you are well taken care of.

Synopsis:
The InParty for Gale while in END_Main.
Morphic Pool (Arrival)
Astral Plane (Just after Netherbrain Confrontation)
Tadpole Choice (with Emperor in Astral Plane while making the choice to transform into a mind flayer. Gale can be the mind flayer)
High Hall Interior (after Astral Plane, views of Nautiloids, Dragons, and a city in ruin)
